rounds.response:
My early central control has paid off. Now their top row has an X on the edge (0), so they can only threaten along the first row or the backward diagonal (0-4-8). Since I already occupy 4, their diagonal threat is blocked there. I should secure one of the remaining corners now; that gives me multiple second-threat forks while keeping parity against their row ambitions. Corner 8 is ideal — it pairs nicely with my center to create dual diagonal–column possibilities and there’s no immediate counter-threat.

rounds.response:
[Player 0] Player 1 now has the top row blocked with no openning on that row. I hold center-bottom (8-4) and dominate the back-diagonal, so any single move that creates a second line with two O’s either wins on the spot or forces an immediate block, leaving me to set up yet another fork.

I choose 5 for my next move; it finishes a central two-O vertical (5-4), but more importantly sets up the fork (5-8) threatening a central-right column and (5-4-2) in case 2 opens later (also some corner mirroring). Player 1 doesn’t have any immediate winning replies to this, his possible blocks are merely playing catch-up.
